":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carlo, Carmine, Geno, Amelio, Aniello, Concetta, Cosmo, Flavio, Gaetano, Gennaro, Mafalda, Raffaele.","Italian: habitational name from any of numerous minor places called Cella or Celle (from <i>cella</i> ‘cell’), because they were once the locations of hermits’ cells."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Volta","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian (northern):","habitational name from any of numerous places called with the word <i>volta</i> ‘turn’, ‘vault’.","from a shortened form of a medieval personal name such as <i>Bonavolta</i>, literally ‘good fortune’, or <i>Malavolta</i> ‘bad fortune’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Igno","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the many given names ending in <i>-gino</i>, e.g. <i>Giorgino</i>, pet form of   Giorgio  , and <i>Luigino</i>, pet form of   Luigi ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Di","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Diana   and   Diane ."],"variants":[{"name":"Diana","meanings":["Name borne in Roman mythology by the goddess of the moon and of hunting, equivalent to the Greek Artemis. In mythology she is characterized as both beautiful and chaste. Her name is of ancient and uncertain derivation. It probably contains a first element that is also found in the name of the Greek god <i>Dionysos</i> (  see  Dennis  ) and the Latin name of the supreme god <i>Jupiter</i>. It was adopted in Britain during the Tudor period as a learned name, a borrowing from Latin influenced by the French form   Diane .  Although it was much used by Elizabethan poets celebrating the virgin goddess and alluding to the Virgin Queen, it was not particularly popular as a given name until the end of the 19th century. In earlier centuries some clergymen were reluctant to baptize girls with this pagan name, mindful of the riots against St Paul stirred up by worshippers of Diana of the Ephesians (Acts 19:24–41). In the late 20th century, its popularity received a boost because of its association with the late  Diana , Princess of Wales (  1961–97 ), who was renowned for her beauty, glamour, and compassion."]},{"name":"Diane","meanings":["form of   Diana  , now also widely used in the English-speaking world. It was especially popular among the Renaissance aristocracy, who loved hunting and were therefore proud to name their daughters after the classical goddess of the chase."]}]},{"name":"Guglielmo","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Igno Di Guglielmo Della Volta was born about 1120, in Genova, Liguria, Italy, his father, Igno Di Guglielmo Della Volta, was 21 and his mother, Cortesina Doria, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Cortesina Doria. He died about 1170, in his hometown, at the age of 52."},"et":{"aproximadamente 1120–aproximadamente 1170":"umbes 1120–umbes 1170","1120–1170":"1120–1170","1100–1170":"1100–1170","112